# Occasi — Developer Guide

A practical guide for adding new templates, fields, and pages to Occasi yourself. Written for someone who has a working dev setup (Netlify + Supabase) and is comfortable editing HTML/CSS/JS by hand.

---

## 1. Project layout at a glance

```
occasi/
├── index.html            Public landing page
├── login.html            Sign in
├── signup.html           Account creation
├── dashboard.html        Customer dashboard (edit site, view RSVPs)
├── rsvp.html             Guest-facing RSVP page (one file, themed by template)
├── templates.html        Template gallery
├── supabase-setup.sql    Initial schema — run once per project
├── migration-v2.sql      Adds created_at + image columns
├── js/occasi-auth.js     Loads Supabase, exposes `supabase` global
├── css/theme.css         Shared dashboard styles (buttons, forms, etc.)
└── assets/logo.png
```

The only two files involved in a "new template" change are **`rsvp.html`** (what guests see) and **`dashboard.html`** (the template dropdown + picker grid).

---

## 2. Adding a new template

Suppose you want to add a **"Tropical Paradise"** template — coral pink + ocean teal.

### 2a. Add a theme block in `rsvp.html`

Inside the `<style>` block, just below the existing `body.theme-rosegold { … }`, paste:

```css
body.theme-tropical{
  --bg:#e6f7f5;
  --bg-grad-from:#e6f7f5;
  --bg-grad-to:#ffe6dc;
  --card:#ffffff;
  --card-soft:#f0fbfa;
  --text:#0f3b3a;
  --muted:#6b8786;
  --line:#c8e7e3;
  --accent:#ff7a5c;
  --accent-strong:#e85a3c;
  --accent-soft:#fde2da;
  --btn:#ff7a5c;
  --btn-hover:#e85a3c;
}
```

The complete set of CSS variables a theme can override:

| Variable | What it controls |
|---|---|
| `--bg-grad-from` / `--bg-grad-to` | Background gradient (top / bottom) |
| `--card` | Form card, error card, success card background |
| `--card-soft` | Inner guest-row card background |
| `--text` | Main text color |
| `--muted` | Secondary text (labels, hints) |
| `--line` | Borders + divider |
| `--accent` | Submit button, focus ring, divider line, ornament |
| `--accent-strong` | Names in success page, "Important" bold text |
| `--accent-soft` | Note background, slideshow fallback tint |
| `--btn` / `--btn-hover` | Submit button base + hover |
| `--display-font` | Couple's name + RSVP title font |
| `--body-font` | Everything else |
| `--ornament` | Character shown in the centre of the divider (e.g. `"❦"`, `"✦"`, `""` for none) |

### 2b. Map the template name to the theme class

Inside `rsvp.html`'s `<script>`, find `TEMPLATE_THEME` and `TEMPLATE_ORNAMENT`. Add a row to each:

```js
var TEMPLATE_THEME = {
  …,
  "Tropical Paradise": "theme-tropical"     // ← add
};
var TEMPLATE_ORNAMENT = {
  …,
  "Tropical Paradise": "🌺"                 // ← add (or "" for none)
};
```

### 2c. List the template in the dashboard picker

Open `dashboard.html`, search for `var TEMPLATES = [`. Add a new entry:

```js
var TEMPLATES = [
  …,
  { n: "Tropical Paradise", d: "Coral + ocean teal, breezy & bright.",
    bg: "linear-gradient(135deg,#e6f7f5,#ffe6dc)", fg: "#0f3b3a" }
];
```

The `bg` and `fg` values render the colour swatch tile in the picker grid — keep them close to your real theme so customers see what they're picking.

### 2d. Test it

Visit `https://your-site/rsvp.html?site=preview&template=Tropical+Paradise` and confirm it renders correctly. Then add a "Try the live demo" link to `index.html` if you want it on the homepage.

That's the entire flow. No build step, no compilation — refresh the page.

---

## 3. Adding new fields to the RSVP form

If you want to capture extra info from guests (e.g. dietary requirements, song requests):

### 3a. Add the column to the database

```sql
alter table public.rsvp_responses
  add column if not exists dietary text,
  add column if not exists song_request text;
```

### 3b. Add the input to `rsvp.html`

In `renderForm()`, the `rows += …` block builds each guest row. Add fields inside the `.guest-row-card` template literal:

```js
'<div class="name-field"><label>Dietary requirements (optional)</label>' +
'<input class="dietary" maxlength="120" autocomplete="off"></div>'
```

### 3c. Read it in the submit handler

In the submit handler, after `lasts[i].value.trim()`, grab the new field:

```js
var dietary = document.querySelectorAll(".dietary")[i].value.trim();
guests.push({ first: f, last: l, dietary: dietary });
```

And in the row map:

```js
return {
  …,
  dietary: g.dietary || null
};
```

### 3d. Show it in the dashboard

In `dashboard.html`'s `loadResponses`, add the field to the rendered card and to the CSV export header / row.

---

## 4. Adding a new page to the dashboard

The dashboard uses simple show/hide sections, no router needed.

1. **Add a sidebar link** — find the `<nav class="side-nav">` block and add:
   ```html
   <a href="#" data-section="gallery">🖼 Gallery</a>
   ```
2. **Add the section div** — below `<div id="page-responses">`, add:
   ```html
   <div class="section-page" id="page-gallery">
     <div class="card"><h2>Gallery</h2>…</div>
   </div>
   ```
3. **Handle the switch** — `switchSection()` already handles any id matching `page-<name>`, so no JS change needed.

---

## 5. Database tables (current state)

```
sites
├── id              uuid pk
├── user_id         uuid → auth.users
├── subdomain       text unique (the URL slug)
├── template_name   text  (matches TEMPLATES entries)
├── status          text  ('draft' | 'live')
└── created_at      timestamptz

site_content
├── site_id          uuid pk → sites.id
├── partner_1        text
├── partner_2        text
├── wedding_date     date
├── rsvp_deadline    date
├── venue_name       text
├── tagline          text
├── invite_size_default int
├── image_url_1      text   ← added by migration-v2
├── image_url_2      text   ← added by migration-v2
└── image_url_3      text   ← added by migration-v2

rsvp_responses
├── id            uuid pk
├── site_id       uuid → sites.id
├── guest_first   text
├── guest_last    text
├── attending     boolean (defaults to true, currently always true)
├── invite_size   int     (size of the group this RSVP was submitted in)
└── created_at    timestamptz default now()  ← added by migration-v2
```

RLS policies: customers can read/write only their own `sites`, `site_content`, and `rsvp_responses`. Guests (anon role) can insert into `rsvp_responses` and read public `sites` rows. See `supabase-setup.sql` for the exact policies.

### Storage

Customer-uploaded photos live in the `site-photos` Supabase Storage bucket at the path `{site_id}/photo-{slot}-{timestamp}.{ext}`. The bucket is public-read so guests can view photos on the RSVP page; uploads, replaces, and deletes are restricted by RLS to the site owner. `image_url_1/2/3` in `site_content` stores the resolved public URLs.

---

## 6. Deploy checklist (new template release)

1. Edit `rsvp.html` (theme + map) and `dashboard.html` (TEMPLATES entry).
2. Test locally or against staging: `?site=preview&template=Your+Template+Name`.
3. Push to git (or drag the folder to Netlify).
4. Hard-refresh in the browser (mobile Safari/Chrome cache aggressively — Cmd/Ctrl+Shift+R on desktop, or close and reopen the tab on mobile).
5. If you added any DB columns: run the matching SQL in Supabase SQL Editor **before** the new front-end goes out.

---

## 7. Common pitfalls

- **Customer says RSVPs are missing.** First click **🔄 Refresh** on the RSVPs tab. If still empty, check that the URL guests are using matches a site that account owns — multi-account confusion is the #1 cause. If you removed the Diagnose button, run this in Supabase SQL Editor:
  ```sql
  select s.subdomain, count(r.*) as rsvps
  from sites s left join rsvp_responses r on r.site_id = s.id
  where s.user_id = (select id from auth.users where email = '<customer-email>')
  group by s.subdomain;
  ```
- **Image won't show on the RSVP page.** Photos upload through the dashboard's photo slots which read from the customer's device — direct URLs are no longer needed. If a customer's upload fails, check (a) Supabase Storage has a `site-photos` bucket with public read, (b) `migration-v2.sql` was run so the RLS policies exist, (c) the file is under 10 MB.
- **Slug already taken.** Slugs are globally unique across all customers. Append a year or short suffix.

---

## 8. Where things live (quick reference)

| Want to change… | Open… | Search for… |
|---|---|---|
| Homepage copy | `index.html` | `hero` |
| Pricing tiers | `index.html` | `pricing` |
| Sign-up flow | `signup.html` | `signUpBtn` |
| Customer dashboard layout | `dashboard.html` | `<aside class="sidebar">` |
| What guests see | `rsvp.html` | `renderForm()` |
| Template colours | `rsvp.html` | `body.theme-` |
| Template list (picker) | `dashboard.html` | `var TEMPLATES =` |
| RSVP list rendering | `dashboard.html` | `loadResponses` |
| CSV export columns | `dashboard.html` | `var csv =` |
| Database schema | `supabase-setup.sql` | (whole file) |

Happy building.
